---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import DocSidebar from '../../components/DocSidebar.astro';
import DocContent from '../../components/DocContent.astro';

const title = 'Getting Started';
const currentPage = '/docs/getting-started';

const content = `
<h2>Prerequisites</h2>
<p>Before you begin, make sure you have the following:</p>
<ul>
  <li>A <strong>Linux machine</strong> (Ubuntu 22.04+ or Debian 12+ recommended)</li>
  <li><strong>Docker</strong> and <strong>Docker Compose</strong> installed</li>
  <li>A <strong>USB webcam</strong> (any UVC-compatible camera works)</li>
  <li>A <strong>USB thermal printer</strong> (ESC/POS compatible, 58mm or 80mm)</li>
  <li>At least 2 GB of free disk space</li>
</ul>

<h2>Quick Start</h2>
<p>Get VibePrint OS running in under 10 minutes:</p>

<h3>1. Clone the repository</h3>
<pre><code>git clone https://github.com/momokii/thermavibe.git
cd thermavibe</code></pre>

<h3>2. Create your environment file</h3>
<pre><code>cp .env.example .env</code></pre>
<p>Open <code>.env</code> and review the default values. For a quick test, the defaults work out of the box with the mock AI and mock payment providers.</p>

<h3>3. Start the stack</h3>
<pre><code>make dev</code></pre>
<p>This runs <code>docker compose up</code> with the development overlay, starting the backend API and PostgreSQL database.</p>

<h3>4. Start the frontend dev server</h3>
<pre><code>cd frontend
npm install
npm run dev</code></pre>
<p>The frontend dev server runs at <code>http://localhost:5173</code> with HMR and auto-proxies API requests to the backend.</p>

<h3>5. Access the application</h3>
<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Service</th><th>URL</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Kiosk UI</td><td><a href="http://localhost:5173">http://localhost:5173</a></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Admin Dashboard</td><td><a href="http://localhost:5173/admin">http://localhost:5173/admin</a></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Backend API</td><td><a href="http://localhost:8000">http://localhost:8000</a></td></tr>
    <tr><td>API Docs (Swagger)</td><td><a href="http://localhost:8000/docs">http://localhost:8000/docs</a></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Health Check</td><td><a href="http://localhost:8000/health">http://localhost:8000/health</a></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Next Steps</h2>
<ul>
  <li>Read the <a href="/docs/architecture">Architecture</a> guide to understand how the system works</li>
  <li>Configure your <a href="/docs/configuration">AI provider and hardware</a> for real usage</li>
  <li>Set up <a href="/docs/deployment">production deployment</a> when you are ready to go live</li>
</ul>

<h2>Hardware Notes</h2>
<p>VibePrint OS is hardware-agnostic. It uses OpenCV/V4L2 for camera capture and <code>python-escpos</code> for direct ESC/POS USB communication. Any USB webcam that appears as a V4L2 device and any thermal printer that supports ESC/POS commands over USB will work without additional drivers.</p>
<p>The camera preview is served as an MJPEG stream from the backend. The frontend never accesses hardware directly — all hardware communication goes through the backend API.</p>
`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Getting Started — VibePrint OS Docs">
  <div style="max-width: 72rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 4rem 1.5rem;">
    <div class="doc-layout" style="display: flex; flex-direction: column;">
      <DocSidebar currentPage={currentPage} />
      <DocContent title={title} content={content} currentPage={currentPage} />
    </div>
  </div>
  <style>
  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    .doc-layout { flex-direction: row !important; }
  }
</style>
</BaseLayout>
